"Harner T.","Organochlorine contamination of the Canadian Arctic, and speculation on future trends",1997,"International Journal of Environment and Pollution","8","1-2",,"51","73",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031341543&partnerID=40&md5=709173ce33534de083e4dc37c3d7b597","Institute for Environmental Studies, Department of Chemical Engineering, University of Toronto, Canada; Atmospheric Environment Service, 4905 Dufferin St., Downsview, Ont., M3H 5T4, Canada","Harner, T., Institute for Environmental Studies, Department of Chemical Engineering, University of Toronto, Canada, Atmospheric Environment Service, 4905 Dufferin St., Downsview, Ont., M3H 5T4, Canada","Emission of organochlorine chemicals in urban, agricultural and industrial regions of the world has resulted in a substantial influx to the Canadian Arctic. Long-range atmospheric transport and what has been referred to as 'global distillation' transport many chemicals from warm source areas to cold, polar regions. Organochlorines are detected in Arctic air, water, and snow, with substantial accumulations in animals, marine mammals, and humans. This has led to concern regarding health effects to native people who consume traditional foods. Speculations on future trends of organochlorines in the Arctic is presented and related to global warming effects and the physical chemistry of the compounds of interest. It is conceivable that high levels of certain contaminants in the Arctic environment may persist for decades despite recent reductions in global emissions.","Arctic; Global warming; Long-range atmospheric transport; Organochlorine contamination; PCBs; Pesticides","Air pollution; Contamination; Global warming; Health hazards; Pesticides; Polychlorinated biphenyls; Snow; Soil pollution; Transport properties; Water pollution; Atmospheric transport; Gas emissions",,,,,,"Ahlborg, U.G., Becking, G.C., Birnbaum, L.S., Brouwer, A., Derks, H.J.G.M., Feeley, M., Golor, G., Yrjanheikki, E., Toxic equivalency factors for dioxin-like PCBs (1994) Chemosphere, 28, pp. 1049-1067; Ayotte, P., Dewailly, E., Bruneau, S., Careau, H., Vezina, A., Arctic air pollution and human health: What effects should be expected? (1994) Sci. Total Environ., 1607, pp. 529-538; Barrie, L.A., Occurrence and trends of pollution in the arctic troposphere (1996) Proceedings of NATO Advanced Studies Workshop on Processes of Chemical Exchange between the Atmosphere and Polar Snow, , Il Ciocco, Italy 19-23 March, 1995; Barrie, L.A., Gregor, D., Hargrave, B., Lake, R., Muir, D.C.G., Shearer, R., Tracey, B., Bidleman, T.F., Arctic contaminants: Sources, occurrence and pathways (1992) Sci. Total Environ., 122, pp. 1-74; Bidleman, T.F., Jantunen, L.M., Falconer, R.L., Barrie, L.A., Decline of hexachlorocyclohexane in the arctic atmosphere and reversal of air-sea gas exchange (1995) Geophys. Res, Lett., 22, pp. 219-222; Cameron, M., Weiss, I.M., Organochlorine contaminants in the country food diet of the Belcher Island Inuit, Northwest Territorities, Canada (1993) Arctic, 46, pp. 42-48; Dewailly, E., Nantel, A., Weber, J.-P., Meyer, F., High levels of PCBs in breast milk of women from arctic Quebec (1989) Bull.Environ. Contam. Toxicol., 43, pp. 641-646; Dewailly, E., Ayotte, P., Bruneau, S., Laliberte, C., Muir, D.C.G., Norstrom, R.J., Inuit exposure to organochlorines through the aquatic food chain in arctic Quebec (1993) Environ. Health Perspect., 101 (7), pp. 618-620. , Poster presentation at the Ninth International Congress on Circumpolar Health, Iceland, June 1993; Duce, R.A., Liss, P.S., Merill, J.T., Atlas, E.I., Buat-Menard, P., Hicks, B.B., Miller, J.M., Zhou, M., The atmospheric input of trace species to the world ocean (1991) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 5, pp. 193-259; Falconer, R.L., Bidleman, T.F., Vapor pressures and predicted particle/gas distributions of polychlorinated biphenyl congeners as functions of temperature and orthochlorine substitution (1994) Atmospheric Environment, 